Piece-by-Piece Breakdown

Let’s look at exactly how each component functions to pull this off seamlessly.

1. Permissions and Setup

At the top of the workflow, we define the event triggers and permissions:

•
pull_request types ensure this runs when code changes or a new PR goes live.

• We explicitly give the job pull-requests: write permissions. Without this, the runner won't be allowed to leave comments on the PR thread.

•
fetch-depth: 0 ensures the full git history is pulled down so we can accurately compare branches.

2. Extracting and Trimming the Diff

git diff "$BASE_SHA...$HEAD_SHA" > diff.txt
head -c 800000 diff.txt > diff_trimmed.txt

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

Instead of relying on heavy ecosystem dependencies, we pull standard git diff text. Huge pull requests can quickly exceed large language model limits or API limits, so head -c 800000 safely caps the payload size at around 800KB to prevent structural drops.

3. The Python Script (Validating Lines and Calling Gemini)

The core logic runs in a dependency-free Python step using standard libraries (urllib). It handles three main problems:

•
Line Target Matching (parse_commentable_lines): LLMs sometimes hallucinate and try to comment on lines that weren't even changed. This function parses the unified diff headers (@@ -line,v +line,v @@) to build a map of lines that actually exist in the new incoming code version.

•
Injecting Context Rules: The prompt_text provides structural guardrails. You can adapt this to fit your specific stack's technical requirements (e.g., advising on UI lifecycles, CSS frameworks, or structural preferences).

•
Enforcing Structured JSON: We define a response_schema directly inside the API request options. This forces the AI model to return raw data exactly matching an object containing a status string, markdown summary, and an array of inline comments.

The script ends by verifying that the AI's feedback strictly lines up with changed lines and writes the output payload into local text files.

4. Submitting the Feedback to GitHub

const reviewEvent = (status === 'issues_found' && comments.length > 0) ? 'REQUEST_CHANGES' : 'COMMENT';
...
await github.rest.pulls.createReview({ ...base, body: summary, comments });

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

The final step uses the official actions/github-script action to process those text files. If the AI flags real logic errors and populates valid comments, the script marks the PR review state as REQUEST_CHANGES. If everything looks clear, it defaults to a standard tracking COMMENT.

If a specific line index mismatch occurs, a try/catch block acts as a fallback to post the core high-level summary review anyway so you don't lose the AI insight.

Make it Your Own

The beauty of this setup is how easy it is to alter. By adjusting the prompt_text section in the Python block, you can easily instruct the LLM to write in a specific language, focus tightly on security vulnerabilities, or ignore everything except your performance benchmarks. Drop the GEMINI_API_KEY into your GitHub repository secrets, and you have an automated, self-hosted code guardrail running completely under your control!

